{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4a2d7611-32f6-4a03-bcb5-002245bfe464","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides no longer exist. The lifecycle is now managed on the **`Window`** class instead.\n\n**Mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` |\n\n**Approach:** Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and return a custom `Window`:\n\n```csharp\n// App.xaml.cs\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    return new MyWindow(new AppShell());\n}\n\n// MyWindow.cs\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart equivalent */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep equivalent */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume equivalent */ }\n}\n```\n\nYou can also subscribe to events (`window.Created += ...`) or use platform-specific lifecycle hooks via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` if you need Android/iOS-specific granularity.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"57f17c28-e68a-4024-9b6d-0a3bcbd5f932","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. Instead of those virtual methods on `Application`, you use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class.\n\n\nActually, I need to correct myself — the `Application` class in .NET MAUI doesn't have those same virtual methods. Instead, you override lifecycle methods directly on the `Window` class, where `Window.Created` maps to the old `OnStart`, `Window.Resumed` corresponds to `OnResume`, and `Window.Stopped` handles what `OnSleep` used to do.\n\nYou can either subscribe to these events or create a custom `Window` subclass that overrides the protected methods like `OnCreated()`, `OnResumed()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnDestroying()`, and a few others for handling backgrounding and activation states.","outputTokens":856,"requestId":"980B:1A0B9E:15D62F7:1869AAC:6A051EDB"},"id":"a8a868b5-2023-4973-9be6-7e4a17d1f191","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:01:30.546Z","parentId":"832cead3-4b5c-4680-a36d-05fad75392d2"}
